                    <abstract>Maria van Antwerpen lived in a number of towns and worked as a seamstress following her sentencing in 1751. While living in Gouda she met Cornelia Swartsenberg who was unwed and pregnant. Maria again assumed a masculine identity, Machiel van Hantwerpen, and went to Zwolle to rejoin the army in 1762. Cornelia followed and they were married in the same year. Machiel resigned from the army two years later and the couple moved to Amsterdam. In 1766 Machiel joined the army, now in service to Amsterdam. In 1769 Machiel was recognised during a trip in Montfoort by someone who knew them as a woman from when Maria had lived in Gouda. Maria was arrested and tried in Gouda and sentenced to exile from Holland and West Friesland.</abstract>
